{"id": "15936", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15936", "title": "June 15", "text": "June 15\n\nBULLET::::- 763 BC – Assyrians record a solar eclipse that is later used to fix the chronology of Mesopotamian history.\nBULLET::::- 844 – Louis II is crowned as king of Italy at Rome by pope Sergius II.\nBULLET::::- 923 – Battle of Soissons: King Robert I of France is killed and King Charles the Simple is arrested by the supporters of Duke Rudolph of Burgundy.\nBULLET::::- 1184 – King Magnus V of Norway is killed at the Battle of Fimreite.\nBULLET::::- 1215 – King John of England puts his seal to Magna Carta.\nBULLET::::- 1219 – Northern Crusades: Danish victory at the Battle of Lindanise (modern-day Tallinn) establishes the Danish Duchy of Estonia.\nBULLET::::- 1246 – With the death of Frederick II, Duke of Austria, the Babenberg dynasty ends in Austria.\nBULLET::::- 1300 – The city of Bilbao is founded.\nBULLET::::- 1312 – At the Battle of Rozgony, King Charles I of Hungary wins a decisive victory over the family of Palatine Amade Aba.\nBULLET::::- 1389 – Battle of Kosovo: The Ottoman Empire defeats Serbs and Bosnians.\nBULLET::::- 1410 – In a decisive battle at Onon River, the Mongol forces of Oljei Temur were decimated by the Chinese armies of the Yongle Emperor.\nBULLET::::- 1502 – Christopher Columbus lands on the island of Martinique on his fourth voyage.\nBULLET::::- 1520 – Pope Leo X threatens to excommunicate Martin Luther in \"Exsurge Domine\".\nBULLET::::- 1648 – Margaret Jones is hanged in Boston for witchcraft in the first such execution for the Massachusetts Bay Colony.\nBULLET::::- 1667 – The first human blood transfusion is administered by Dr. Jean-Baptiste Denys.\nBULLET::::- 1670 – The first stone of Fort Ricasoli is laid down in Malta.\nBULLET::::- 1752 – Benjamin Franklin proves that lightning is electricity (traditional date, the exact date is unknown).\nBULLET::::- 1776 – Delaware Separation Day: Delaware votes to suspend government under the British Crown and separate officially from Pennsylvania.\nBULLET::::- 1800 – The Provisional Army of the United States is dissolved.\nBULLET::::- 1804 – New Hampshire approves the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, ratifying the document.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – Joseph Bonaparte becomes King of Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1836 – Arkansas is admitted as the 25th U.S. state.\nBULLET::::- 1844 – Charles Goodyear receives a patent for vulcanization, a process to strengthen rubber.\nBULLET::::- 1846 – The Oregon Treaty establishes the 49th parallel as the border between the United States and Canada, from the Rocky Mountains to the Strait of Juan de Fuca.\nBULLET::::- 1859 – Pig War: Ambiguity in the Oregon Treaty leads to the \"Northwestern Boundary Dispute\" between United States and British/Canadian settlers.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – American Civil War: The Second Battle of Petersburg begins.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Arlington National Cemetery is established when of the Arlington estate (formerly owned by Confederate General Robert E. Lee) are officially set aside as a military cemetery by U.S. Secretary of War Edwin M. Stanton.\nBULLET::::- 1877 – Henry Ossian Flipper becomes the first African American cadet to graduate from the United States Military Academy.\nBULLET::::- 1878 – Eadweard Muybridge takes a series of photographs to prove that all four feet of a horse leave the ground when it runs; the study becomes the basis of motion pictures.\nBULLET::::- 1888 – Crown Prince Wilhelm becomes Kaiser Wilhelm II; he will be the last Emperor of the German Empire. Due to the death of his predecessors Wilhelm I and Frederick III, 1888 is the Year of the Three Emperors.\nBULLET::::- 1896 – The deadliest tsunami in Japan's history kills more than 22,000 people.\nBULLET::::- 1904 – A fire aboard the steamboat in New York City's East River kills 1,000.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – United States President Woodrow Wilson signs a bill incorporating the Boy Scouts of America, making them the only American youth organization with a federal charter.\nBULLET::::- 1919 – John Alcock and Arthur Brown complete the first nonstop transatlantic flight when they reach Clifden, County Galway, Ireland.\nBULLET::::- 1920 – A new border treaty between Germany and Denmark gives northern Schleswig to Denmark.\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Bessie Coleman earns her pilot's license, becoming the first female pilot of African-American descent.\nBULLET::::- 1934 – The United States Great Smoky Mountains National Park is founded.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – First flight of the Vickers Wellington bomber.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – A German expedition led by Karl Wien loses sixteen members in an avalanche on Nanga Parbat. It is the worst single disaster to occur on an 8000m peak.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: Operation Ariel begins: Allied troops start to evacuate France, following Germany's takeover of Paris and most of the nation.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – World War II: Battle of Saipan: The United States invade Japanese-occupied Saipan.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – In the Saskatchewan general election, the CCF, led by Tommy Douglas, is elected and forms the first socialist government in North America.\nBULLET::::- 1970 – Charles Manson goes on trial for the Sharon Tate murders.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Red Army Faction co-founder Ulrike Meinhof is captured by police in Langenhagen.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – After the death of dictator Francisco Franco in 1975, the first democratic elections took place in Spain on this day.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – King Hussein of Jordan marries American Lisa Halaby, who takes the name Queen Noor.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – Rembrandt's painting \"Danaë\" is attacked by a man (later judged insane) who throws sulfuric acid on the canvas and cuts it twice with a knife.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – In the Philippines, Mount Pinatubo erupts in the second largest volcanic eruption of the 20th century, killing over 800 people.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – The United States Supreme Court rules in \"United States v. Álvarez-Machaín\" that it is permissible for the United States to forcibly extradite suspects in foreign countries and bring them to the United States for trial, without approval from those other countries.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – Israel and Vatican City establish full diplomatic relations.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – The Troubles: The Provisional Irish Republican Army (IRA) detonates a powerful truck bomb in the middle of Manchester, England, devastating the city centre and injuring 200 people.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Leaders of the People's Republic of China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan formed the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – Nik Wallenda becomes the first person to successfully tightrope walk directly over Niagara Falls.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – A bomb explodes on a bus in the Pakistani city of Quetta, killing at least 25 people and wounding 22 others.\nBULLET::::- 1330 – Edward, the Black Prince of England (d. 1376)\nBULLET::::- 1423 – Gabriele Sforza, Archbishop of Milan (d. 1457)\nBULLET::::- 1479 – Lisa del Giocondo, Italian model, subject of the \"Mona Lisa\" (d. 1542)\nBULLET::::- 1519 – Henry FitzRoy, 1st Duke of Richmond and Somerset, English politician, Lord Lieutenant of Ireland (d. 1536)\nBULLET::::- 1542 – Richard Grenville, English captain and explorer (d. 1591)\nBULLET::::- 1549 – Elizabeth Knollys, English noblewoman (d. 1605)\nBULLET::::- 1553 – Archduke Ernest of Austria (d. 1595)\nBULLET::::- 1605 – Thomas Randolph, English poet and playwright (d. 1635)\nBULLET::::- 1618 – François Blondel, French architect (d. 1686)\nBULLET::::- 1623 – Cornelis de Witt, Dutch politician (d. 1672)\nBULLET::::- 1624 – Hiob Ludolf, German orientalist and philologist (d. 1704)\nBULLET::::- 1640 – Bernard Lamy, French mathematician and theologian (d. 1715)\nBULLET::::- 1645 – Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, English politician (d. 1712)\nBULLET::::- 1749 – Georg Joseph Vogler, German organist, composer, and theorist (d. 1814)\