ccurs in Madrid during the Spanish transition to democracy.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – Soviet satellite Kosmos 954, with a nuclear reactor on board, burns up in Earth's atmosphere, scattering radioactive debris over Canada's Northwest Territories. Only 1% is recovered.\nBULLET::::- 1984 – Apple Computer places the Macintosh personal computer on sale in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – Notorious serial killer Ted Bundy, with over 30 known victims, is executed by the electric chair at the Florida State Prison.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – Japan launches Hiten, the country's first lunar probe, the first robotic lunar probe since the Soviet Union's Luna 24 in 1976, and the first lunar probe launched by a country other than Soviet Union or the United States.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – The United States Department of Homeland Security officially begins operation.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – Cyclone Klaus makes landfall near Bordeaux, France, causing 26 deaths as well as extensive disruptions to public transport and power supplies.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – At least 35 die and 180 are injured in a bombing at Moscow's Domodedovo Airport.\n\nBULLET::::- AD 76 – Hadrian, Roman emperor (d. 138)\nBULLET::::- 1287 – Richard de Bury, English bishop and politician, Lord Chancellor of Great Britain (d. 1345)\nBULLET::::- 1444 – Galeazzo Maria Sforza, Duke of Milan (d. 1476)\nBULLET::::- 1540 – Edmund Campion, English priest and martyr (d. 1581)\nBULLET::::- 1547 – Joanna of Austria, Grand Duchess of Tuscany, Austrian Archduchess (d. 1578)\nBULLET::::- 1602 – Mildmay Fane, 2nd Earl of Westmorland, English politician (d. 1666)\nBULLET::::- 1619 – Yamazaki Ansai, Japanese philosopher (d. 1682)\nBULLET::::- 1643 – Charles Sackville, 6th Earl of Dorset, English poet and politician, Lord Chamberlain of Great Britain (d. 1706)\nBULLET::::- 1664 – John Vanbrugh, English architect and dramatist (d. 1726)\nBULLET::::- 1670 – William Congreve, English playwright and poet (d. 1729)\nBULLET::::- 1672 – Margrave Albert Freder